    "tierDistribution": "Exceptional quality: 96.55% Tier 1 sources (28/29 projections) - highest tier percentage across all domains completed. Only 1 Tier 2 projection (Associate Satisfaction) where aggregated benchmarks used vs specific primary research.",
    "sourceTypes": "Comprehensive mix of vendor case studies (Zebra, Loomis, Legion, StopLift, ParallelDots), industry research (NRF, RSR Research), government reports (U.S. Dept of Labor), and analyst studies (Forrester TEI), providing multi-sourced validation.",
    "causalMechanisms": "All 29 projections include detailed causal explanations of HOW store operations transformation achieves results, with specific technology mechanisms (AI photo verification, smart safes, automated scheduling, mobile communications) and contextual bounds.",
    "vendorCoverage": "Strong representation from leading store operations technology vendors across all six capability areas: Zebra/Bindy (task management), Loomis/Brinks (cash management), StopLift/Agilence (loss prevention), Legion/Kronos (labor scheduling).",
    "metricSpecificity": "All projections quantified with specific ranges and comparative baselines enabling defensible ROI calculations. Many include dollar savings examples (e.g., $250K-$500K labor savings for $50M retailer).",
    "implementationContext": "Projections include practical requirements (mobile connectivity, POS integration, HD cameras, rules engines) and acknowledge variation factors (store size, volume, current efficiency levels, associate adoption).",
    "realWorldValidation": "Multiple case studies with named retailers (Office Depot, Goodwill of SW Pennsylvania) and specific measurable outcomes provide real-world validation beyond vendor claims."
  },
  "researchNotes": {
    "methodology": "Systematic capability-by-capability research using web search for 2024 vendor case studies, industry benchmarks, government reports, and analyst research. Cross-validated metrics across multiple sources where available. Applied conservative estimates accounting for implementation variation.",
    "challenges": "Some niche metrics (associate satisfaction improvement) lack published 2024 primary research with specific statistical validation, requiring Tier 2 aggregated benchmarks. Most metrics had strong Tier 1 vendor case study or industry research support.",
    "strengths": "Store operations extremely well-documented domain with extensive vendor case study data (Zebra, Loomis, Legion, StopLift all publish client results), government enforcement data (DOL wage violations), and industry benchmark research (NRF shrink survey, RSR retail research) enabling high-confidence projections.",
    "crossValidation": "Multiple projections validated across capabilities - e.g., audit time reduction metrics consistent across task management (50-60%), compliance audits (to 10-20% of DM time), and communications (70-80% follow-up time reduction), suggesting reliable patterns.",
    "nextSteps": "Consider SME validation workshop with store operations experts (district managers, loss prevention directors, HR managers) to review projections for real-world implementation factors. Quarterly refresh recommended as vendors publish new case studies and NRF releases annual shrink survey."
  }
